# zypper — opensuse package manager primer
#
# zypper is opensuse's package tool (also used on suse linux enterprise).
# rpm under the hood, like dnf, but with a different command surface and
# a few suse-specific concepts.
#
# command surface mixes full-english subcommands with short aliases. you'll
# see both in the wild; either form works.
#
#   in   install         rm   remove           up   update (bounded)
#   dup  dist-upgrade    ref  refresh          se   search
#   if   info            wp   what-provides    ps   processes (after-upgrade)
#   lr   list repos      ar   add repo         mr   modify repo
#   rr   remove repo     al   add lock         rl   remove lock     ll   list locks
#   lp   list-patches    patch                  pchk patch-check
#
# the two suse-specific concepts to internalize early:
#
# - PATTERNS — like dnf groups: named bundles of packages.
#     `devel_basis` is the famous one (gcc, make, etc.).
# - PATCHES — security / bugfix collections that map onto specific bugs
#     or CVEs. `zypper patch` installs only patches, not random updates.
#
# config: /etc/zypp/zypp.conf and one file per repo in /etc/zypp/repos.d/.
#
# tumbleweed vs leap:
# - tumbleweed (rolling): `zypper dup` IS the daily update command.
#   `zypper up` is wrong on tumbleweed — it can't cross release boundaries
#   it doesn't know are there.
# - leap (point release): `zypper up` for daily; `zypper dup --releasever=N.N`
#   for the major-version upgrade.


REFRESH / INSTALL / UPGRADE
---------------------------

# refresh metadata for all enabled repos
sudo zypper refresh
sudo zypper ref

# upgrade installed packages WITHOUT crossing version / repo boundaries.
# right command on Leap; wrong command on Tumbleweed.
sudo zypper update
sudo zypper up

# distribution upgrade — full solver pass, can change vendors, swap
# packages, accept arch transitions. right command on Tumbleweed daily,
# and the way to bump Leap to a new minor release.
sudo zypper dup

# non-interactive (scripts, dockerfiles)
sudo zypper --non-interactive update
sudo zypper -n up

# show what would update without doing it
zypper lu                              # list-updates
zypper list-patches                    # only the security/bugfix patches

# install one or more packages
sudo zypper install neovim git
sudo zypper in neovim git

# install but skip "recommended" weak deps (smaller install, fewer surprises)
sudo zypper install --no-recommends neovim

# install from a local .rpm file (deps still resolved from repos)
sudo zypper install ./mypackage-1.0-1.x86_64.rpm

# install from a specific repo when the same pkg lives in several
sudo zypper install --from packman ffmpeg

# allow zypper to swap a package's vendor — needed the first time you
# pull a codec build from packman over the openSUSE original.
sudo zypper install --allow-vendor-change vlc

# install just security/bugfix patches
sudo zypper patch
sudo zypper patch --category security


REMOVE
------

# remove a package. by default zypper does NOT auto-remove orphaned deps —
# this differs from dnf / pacman -Rs / apk del. add --clean-deps if you
# want apt-autoremove-style behavior.
sudo zypper remove neovim
sudo zypper rm neovim
sudo zypper rm --clean-deps neovim

# show what would be removed
sudo zypper rm --dry-run neovim

# clean orphaned packages (the explicit "autoremove" sweep)
zypper packages --orphaned
sudo zypper remove $(zypper packages --orphaned | awk -F'|' '/^i/{print $3}')


QUERY (installed packages)
--------------------------

# list every installed package
zypper search --installed-only
zypper se -i

# count installed packages
rpm -qa | wc -l

# what's already installed for this name?
zypper info neovim

# files installed by a package (rpm answers; zypper doesn't have a
# direct equivalent)
rpm -ql neovim

# which installed package owns this file?
rpm -qf /usr/bin/nvim

# what depends on this package?
zypper info --requires neovim
rpm -q --whatrequires neovim

# what does this package depend on?
zypper info --recommends --requires --suggests neovim

# install date / size
rpm -qa --last | head -20
rpm -qi neovim


SEARCH (not yet installed)
--------------------------

# search by name + summary, both repos and installed
zypper search neovim
zypper se neovim

# only available (not installed)
zypper se -u neovim
zypper search --uninstalled-only neovim

# search by capability — answers "which package provides this file or lib?"
zypper what-provides /usr/bin/strings
zypper wp 'libssl.so.3()(64bit)'

# verbose search with version + repo of each match
zypper se -v neovim

# search patterns (suse package groups)
zypper se -t pattern
zypper se -t pattern devel

# what's actually in a pattern?
zypper info -t pattern devel_basis


CACHE
-----

# package cache lives at /var/cache/zypp/packages/
ls /var/cache/zypp/packages/

# clean package files (keeps metadata)
sudo zypper clean

# nuke everything — packages + metadata + raw cache
sudo zypper clean --all

# clean metadata only (use when a repo's index is misbehaving)
sudo zypper clean --metadata

# force a fresh metadata refresh after cleaning
sudo zypper ref -f


REPOSITORIES
------------

# list every configured repo
zypper lr
zypper lr -d                           # with URIs, priority, GPG info
zypper lr -p                           # sorted by priority

# per-repo files
ls /etc/zypp/repos.d/

# add a repo. the second arg is the alias zypper will use to refer to it.
sudo zypper ar -f http://download.opensuse.org/repositories/foo/foo
sudo zypper ar https://example.com/some-repo.repo

# disable / enable a repo
sudo zypper mr -d repo-alias
sudo zypper mr -e repo-alias

# change repo priority. lower number = higher priority. default is 99.
# this is how you keep packman's ffmpeg from being overridden by an oss
# update — set packman lower (higher priority) than the default repos.
sudo zypper mr -p 90 packman

# refresh just one repo
sudo zypper ref repo-alias

# remove a repo
sudo zypper rr repo-alias


# packman — the third-party codecs / multimedia repo (rpm fusion analog).
# add and switch to its versions of multimedia packages:
sudo zypper ar -cfp 90 https://ftp.gwdg.de/pub/linux/misc/packman/suse/openSUSE_Tumbleweed/ packman
sudo zypper ref
sudo zypper dup --from packman --allow-vendor-change

# OBS (Open Build Service) — opensuse's user / community build infra.
# closer in spirit to fedora's COPR than to arch's AUR — prebuilt binaries.
# search projects at https://software.opensuse.org/
sudo zypper ar https://download.opensuse.org/repositories/some:project/openSUSE_Tumbleweed/some:project.repo
sudo zypper ref
sudo zypper in some-package


PATTERNS (groups) AND PATCHES
-----------------------------

# patterns are named bundles — closest analog to dnf groups. install a
# whole pattern in one shot.
zypper search --type pattern
sudo zypper install --type pattern devel_basis

# what does the pattern actually pull in?
zypper info -t pattern devel_basis

# patches are security and bugfix collections (one patch ~ one bug or
# CVE), distinct from arbitrary version updates.
zypper list-patches
zypper list-patches --category security
zypper list-patches --severity critical

# install all pending patches
sudo zypper patch
sudo zypper patch --category security
sudo zypper patch --cve CVE-2024-12345

# scan: is the system fully patched?
zypper patch-check


LOCKING / PINNING / DOWNGRADING
-------------------------------

# lock a package — it won't update, install, or remove until unlocked.
# this is the dnf-versionlock / pacman-IgnorePkg analog.
sudo zypper addlock neovim
sudo zypper al neovim

# list locks
zypper locks
zypper ll

# remove a lock
sudo zypper removelock neovim
sudo zypper rl neovim

# locks live in /etc/zypp/locks
cat /etc/zypp/locks

# downgrade — zypper has no dedicated `downgrade` subcommand. either
# install a specific version explicitly (if still in a repo or in the
# cache) or install the .rpm file directly:
sudo zypper in 'neovim<0.10.0'                     # specific version-range
sudo zypper in --oldpackage ./neovim-0.9.5-1.x86_64.rpm


SNAPSHOTS AND ROLLBACK (SNAPPER)
--------------------------------

# opensuse defaults to btrfs on /, with snapper auto-creating a "pre" and
# "post" snapshot around every zypper transaction. this is one of the
# best parts of running opensuse — failed update? roll back.

# list snapshots (most recent at the bottom)
sudo snapper list

# what changed between two snapshots?
sudo snapper status 42..43
sudo snapper diff 42..43 /etc/somefile

# undo the last zypper transaction by rolling back to its "pre" snapshot.
# safe and reversible.
sudo snapper rollback                  # rolls back to the default-selected snapshot
sudo snapper rollback 42               # roll back to a specific snapshot
sudo reboot

# undo a transaction the targeted way — without changing the default root
sudo snapper undochange 42..43

# clean up snapshot accumulation if disk gets tight
sudo snapper cleanup number
sudo snapper cleanup timeline

# zypper's own "after upgrade, what's still using stale files?" tool —
# functionally the same as dnf needs-restarting.
sudo zypper ps -s


DISTRIBUTION UPGRADE
--------------------

# tumbleweed (rolling): there's nothing to do but `dup`.
sudo zypper ref
sudo zypper dup

# leap N → N+1 (point release upgrade). edit the repos to point to the
# new release THEN dup. snapper has your back if it goes wrong.
sudo zypper --releasever=15.7 ref
sudo zypper --releasever=15.7 dup --allow-vendor-change

# alternative for leap upgrades — `opensuse-migration-tool` (newer) drives
# the same dup flow with safer defaults.
sudo zypper in opensuse-migration-tool
sudo opensuse-migration-tool


COMMON DEV TOOLS
----------------

# the conventional bootstrap on opensuse — devel_basis pulls in gcc,
# make, autoconf, automake, binutils, glibc-devel, etc.
sudo zypper install --type pattern devel_basis
sudo zypper install git

# see what the pattern actually pulls in
zypper info -t pattern devel_basis

# editors / shells
sudo zypper install neovim vim tmux zsh

# languages and runtimes
sudo zypper install python3 python3-pip nodejs npm go rust cargo \
    clang cmake ninja

# debug / inspection
sudo zypper install gdb lldb strace ltrace valgrind perf

# containers / vms
sudo zypper install podman buildah skopeo
sudo zypper install qemu-kvm virt-manager libvirt

# handy CLI
sudo zypper install ripgrep fd bat fzf jq htop wget curl unzip

# notes:
# - python on opensuse is python3. system pip is PEP-668-locked — use
#   venvs (`python3 -m venv .venv`) or pipx for global CLI tools.
# - opensuse, like fedora, leans podman over docker by default.
# - for rust prefer rustup (it's in the official repos) over the bare
#   `rust`+`cargo` rpms when you need multiple toolchains:
sudo zypper install rustup
rustup default stable


